## 5. DATABASE DESIGN

These are the only 6 tables this MVP needs. Do not add more without asking.

products
  id | name | description | timestamps

raw_materials
  id | name | uom | description | timestamps

bill_of_materials
  id | product_id (FK) | raw_material_id (FK) | quantity_per_unit

vendors
  id | name | country | contact_name | contact_email | timestamps

Status ENUM values:
  purchase_requests.status → draft | submitted | approved | cancelled
  rfqs.status              → draft | sent | closed

Number formats (generated in Service layer, never manually):
  pr_number  → PR-YYYYMMDD-XXXX
  rfq_number → RFQ-YYYYMMDD-XXXX

---

## 6. ARCHITECTURE LOGIC
Layer responsibilities — never mix these:

CONTROLLER  → receives request, calls service, returns view or redirect
SERVICE     → all business logic lives here, talks to models
MODEL       → Eloquent relationships and scopes only
FORM REQUEST → all validation, business-friendly error messages
BLADE VIEW  → display only, zero logic except simple loops and conditionals

The PDF generation flow specifically:
  RFQController::downloadPdf()
    → calls PDFGeneratorService::generate(RFQ $rfq)
       → loads rfqs/pdf.blade.php as HTML
       → converts to PDF via DomPDF
       → returns download response

---

## 7. CONSULTANT BEHAVIOR — NON-NEGOTIABLE

When I give you a requirement:
- Identify what business outcome it serves before writing code
- Flag any assumption about business logic explicitly
- If a decision has tradeoffs, name them in one sentence
- Suggest a better approach if you see one — but build what I decide
- Think about the end user: a factory planner or purchasing officer
  who is not technical and needs clarity in the UI

Example of the thinking I expect:
  I say: "Add a status field to PR"
  BAD response: adds a status column and moves on
  GOOD response: "PR status drives the workflow. I'll use:
    draft → submitted → approved → cancelled.
    This gives the purchasing officer a clear handoff point
    and gives management an audit trail. Confirming before I build."

---

## 8. CODE RULES

- Business logic belongs in Services, never in Controllers or Models
- Use Eloquent relationships — never raw SQL
- Use Form Requests for all validation
- Use named routes everywhere — no hardcoded URLs
- Use soft deletes on PurchaseRequest and RFQ (these are business documents)
- Seed realistic test data so the MVP can be demoed immediately
- PDF Blade template uses inline styles only (DomPDF limitation)

---

## 9. DEFINITION OF DONE

A feature is done when:
✅ Business logic is correct and lives in the Service
✅ Validation exists in Form Request with clear error messages
✅ Works end-to-end: form → database → correct output
✅ No hardcoded values, no dd(), no TODO left behind
✅ Can be demoed to a non-technical factory manager without confusion